---
/**
 * Pilcrow Playground — Preview pane (sub-task 7 of PILCROW_PLAYGROUND_PLAN.md).
 *
 * Wires `BrowserRenderer` (from `src/lib/playground/browser-renderer.ts`) to
 * the playground's right column. Listens for `pilcrow:editor-changed` events
 * dispatched by Editor.astro, runs the markdown source through the typeset
 * pipeline, and replaces the preview content with per-line `<span class="pt-line">`
 * spans wrapped in a real `.post-body` host (so the production CSS — including
 * `--prose-measure: 65ch` — applies natively).
 *
 * ─── Pinned design constraint (from sub-task 7 brief) ────────────────────────
 *   The preview *pane* (this section) is the wide right column on desktop.
 *   The typeset *output* renders at 65ch — Pilcrow's canonical measure, set
 *   by `global.css` and produced naturally by BrowserRenderer.
 *   The output sits **centred in the pane with generous surrounding margin**.
 *   The pane is the frame; the typeset is the picture.
 *
 *   Implementation: don't pass a `maxWidth` override to BrowserRenderer.typeset()
 *   — let it derive from `--prose-measure` via `resolveProseMeasurePx()`.
 *   The pane wrapper provides the centred container + breathing margins.
 *
 * ─── Design Q&A resolutions (defaults applied; see sub-task 7 brief) ─────────
 *   Q A (event contract): (b) — `pilcrow:editor-changed` CustomEvent on
 *     `document`. Detail shape (THE CONTRACT for sub-tasks 6, 8, 9):
 *
 *         CustomEventInit<{
 *           markdown: string;
 *           source: 'paste' | 'keystroke' | 'init';
 *         }>
 *
 *     Editor.astro is the dispatcher; Preview.astro is the listener. Future
 *     dispatchers (sub-task 6 settings panel: `pilcrow:settings-changed`;
 *     sub-task 9 share-URL: `pilcrow:share-state-loaded`) follow the same
 *     pattern (CustomEvent on `document`, `detail` carries typed payload).
 *
 *   Q B (debounce): (e) smart — paste = immediate, keystrokes = debounced
 *     150ms. The 150ms threshold is below perceptual lag (~200ms) and well
 *     above BrowserRenderer's typical ~30ms typeset cost. Editor.astro is
 *     responsible for the debounce + source-tagging; Preview just listens.
 *
 *   Q C (initial render timing): (b) — client-render on script load with a
 *     reserved height to prevent layout shift. NO loading text (the actual
 *     typeset cost after wasm warmup is sub-100ms). Eager BrowserRenderer
 *     `open()` on page load: wasm fetch and font weight requests run in
 *     background while the user reads the stand-in HTML fallback. By the
 *     time they paste/type, the renderer is warm.
 *
 *   Q D (error handling): (a) — graceful degradation. If BrowserRenderer
 *     init or typeset() throws, the preview falls back to the markdown
 *     source rendered as plain HTML paragraphs (split on blank lines —
 *     no new dep needed; the playground stand-in is plain prose). A single
 *     muted line at the top surfaces the failure honestly:
 *     "Pilcrow's typesetter couldn't initialise — showing plain HTML."
 *
 *   Q E (settings shape): forward declaration only — first version uses
 *     hard-coded defaults that match the published site:
 *       - `dropCap: true`
 *       - NO `maxWidth` override (let `--prose-measure` derive 65ch)
 *       - NO `fontShorthand` override (let probe-paragraph derivation pick
 *         up the .post-body cascade)
 *       - NO `lineHeight` override (let probe-paragraph derivation pick up
 *         CSS `line-height: 1.7`)
 *     Sub-task 6 will swap these for live reads from the settings panel.
 *
 * ─── JS-disabled fallback ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
 *   The pane server-renders the same stand-in prose as plain HTML paragraphs
 *   (no markdown library needed — the stand-in is a single paragraph of plain
 *   text). With JS off the user sees readable Fraunces-set prose at 65ch
 *   inside the pane — not a typeset (no pretext line breaks) but legible,
 *   intentional, on-brand. The hydration script then upgrades this to the
 *   typeset version when JS is available.
 */

// Stand-in prose — verbatim copy of Editor.astro's STAND_IN_PROSE so the
// initial preview render matches the editor's initial value byte-for-byte.
// (Sub-task 5's editor uses this string as `data-stand-in="true"` content.)
const STAND_IN_PROSE =
  "The cheapest signal a writer can send is the one buried in their type. " +
  "Set the same paragraph in two faces and the reader feels two different " +
  "writers — one calmer, one more insistent — without ever naming the " +
  "difference. Editorial typography is the part of writing that travels " +
  "under the words, doing its work before the reader knows there was work " +
  "to do, and Pilcrow exists to put that work back in reach for the open web.";
---

<h2 id="playground-preview-label" class="preview-label">Preview</h2>

{/* The typeset frame — the centred container that holds the .post-body
    host. Its job is positioning + padding; the typeset itself sits inside
    at its natural 65ch width. The reserved min-height prevents layout
    shift between the JS-disabled fallback and the typeset upgrade. */}
<div class="preview-frame">
  <div
    id="playground-preview-host"
    class="post-body"
    aria-live="polite"
    data-preview-state="initial"
  >
    {/* JS-disabled fallback: plain prose paragraph rendered at SSR.
        BrowserRenderer's hydration replaces this innerHTML on first init.
        The .post-body class above ensures `--prose-measure: 65ch` and the
        editorial cascade apply identically to the typeset that will replace
        this content. */}
    <p>{STAND_IN_PROSE}</p>
  </div>
  {/* Failure notice — hidden by default; toggled visible by the script if
      BrowserRenderer init or typeset() throws. Q D resolution. Inter,
      muted, single line. */}
  <p
    id="playground-preview-fallback-notice"
    class="preview-fallback-notice"
    hidden
  >
    Pilcrow's typesetter couldn't initialise — showing plain HTML.
  </p>
</div>

<script>
  /**
   * Preview hydration — wires BrowserRenderer to the editor event contract.
   *
   * Lifecycle:
   *   1. On script load: instantiate BrowserRenderer, eagerly call open().
   *      Wasm fetch + font weight loads happen in background while the user
   *      reads the SSR stand-in fallback.
   *   2. Once open() resolves: typeset the stand-in to land the first real
   *      preview (source: 'init'). Layout shift is bounded by the reserved
   *      min-height on `.preview-frame`.
   *   3. Listen for `pilcrow:editor-changed` events. Each event runs typeset
   *      with the new markdown; on failure, fall back to plain-HTML paragraph
   *      rendering and surface the muted notice.
   *
   * The script is intentionally small and self-contained. Sub-tasks 6, 8, 9
   * will dispatch their own events on `document` (e.g.
   * `pilcrow:settings-changed`) — when they ship, this listener gets a
   * companion that re-typesets with the new options. The contract is the
   * CustomEvent + `detail` shape, not a shared bus.
   */

  import { BrowserRenderer } from '../../lib/playground/browser-renderer.ts';

  // ─── Event contract — the typed surface sub-tasks 6/9 build against ─────
  interface EditorChangedDetail {
    markdown: string;
    source: 'paste' | 'keystroke' | 'init';
  }

  // ─── DOM handles ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  const host = document.getElementById(
    'playground-preview-host',
  ) as HTMLDivElement | null;
  const fallbackNotice = document.getElementById(
    'playground-preview-fallback-notice',
  ) as HTMLParagraphElement | null;

  if (host && fallbackNotice) {
    // Stand-in prose — kept in sync with Editor.astro (and the SSR fallback
    // above) so the first typeset matches the editor's initial value. If
    // Editor.astro changes its stand-in copy, update both.
    const STAND_IN =
      "The cheapest signal a writer can send is the one buried in their type. " +
      "Set the same paragraph in two faces and the reader feels two different " +
      "writers — one calmer, one more insistent — without ever naming the " +
      "difference. Editorial typography is the part of writing that travels " +
      "under the words, doing its work before the reader knows there was work " +
      "to do, and Pilcrow exists to put that work back in reach for the open web.";

    // ─── Plain-HTML fallback (Q D) ────────────────────────────────────────
    // No markdown library — the playground v0 stand-in is plain prose. The
    // converter splits on blank lines and wraps each block in <p>. HTML-
    // escapes input so user-pasted content can't inject script tags.
    const escapeHTML = (s: string): string =>
      s
        .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
        .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
        .replace(/>/g, '&gt;');

    const markdownToPlainHTML = (md: string): string => {
      const blocks = md
        .split(/\n{2,}/)
        .map((b) => b.trim())
        .filter((b) => b.length > 0);
      if (blocks.length === 0) return '<p></p>';
      return blocks.map((b) => `<p>${escapeHTML(b)}</p>`).join('\n');
    };

    // ─── Markdown → HTML (input to BrowserRenderer) ───────────────────────
    // BrowserRenderer expects HTML (a `.post-body` body), not raw markdown.
    // For sub-task 7 the playground's stand-in is plain prose with no
    // markdown formatting; the same blank-line-to-paragraph conversion that
    // powers the Q D fallback also works as the input transform. Sub-task 6
    // (or whenever Pilcrow's markdown pipeline gets ported to the browser)
    // can swap this for the real remark/rehype directive pipeline.
    const sourceToBodyHTML = (md: string): string => markdownToPlainHTML(md);

    // ─── Typeset state ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    const renderer = new BrowserRenderer();
    let rendererReady = false;
    let lastFailed = false;
    // Coalesce overlapping typeset() calls — only the latest source wins.
    let pendingMarkdown: string | null = null;
    let typesetting = false;

    const showFallback = (md: string, message?: string): void => {
      lastFailed = true;
      host.innerHTML = markdownToPlainHTML(md);
      host.dataset.previewState = 'fallback';
      fallbackNotice.hidden = false;
      if (message) {
        // eslint-disable-next-line no-console
        console.warn('[pilcrow:preview]', message);
      }
    };

    const clearFallback = (): void => {
      if (lastFailed) {
        lastFailed = false;
        fallbackNotice.hidden = true;
      }
    };

    const runTypeset = async (md: string, source: EditorChangedDetail['source']): Promise<void> => {
      // Coalesce: if a typeset is in flight, queue the latest input and let
      // the running call pick it up when it finishes.
      if (typesetting) {
        pendingMarkdown = md;
        return;
      }
      typesetting = true;
      try {
        const bodyHTML = sourceToBodyHTML(md);
        // No `maxWidth` — let resolveProseMeasurePx() derive 65ch from CSS.
        // No `fontShorthand` — let probe-paragraph derivation pick it up.
        // No `lineHeight` — same.
        // TODO sub-task 6: read `dropCap`, font, measure, line-height from
        // the settings panel via getElementById on the settings inputs.
        const result = await renderer.typeset(bodyHTML, {
          fontShorthand: '',
          maxWidth: 0,
          lineHeight: 0,
          dropCap: true,
          postPath: `playground (${source})`,
        });
        host.innerHTML = result.html;
        host.dataset.previewState = source === 'init' ? 'initial-typeset' : 'live';
        clearFallback();
      } catch (err) {
        showFallback(md, `typeset failed (source=${source}): ${(err as Error).message}`);
      } finally {
        typesetting = false;
        // Drain queued input — if a newer event arrived during the run,
        // process it now. This guarantees the preview reflects the *latest*
        // editor state, not whichever event happened to win the race.
        if (pendingMarkdown !== null) {
          const next = pendingMarkdown;
          pendingMarkdown = null;
          // Re-enter via the same code path; tag as 'keystroke' since we
          // can't recover the original source and 'keystroke' is the
          // benign default.
          void runTypeset(next, 'keystroke');
        }
      }
    };

    // ─── Eager BrowserRenderer.open() (Q C sub-question) ──────────────────
    // Kicks off wasm fetch + Fraunces weight loads in the background. The
    // user sees the SSR plain-HTML fallback in the meantime, which is
    // already styled (Fraunces, 65ch, paper bg) — only line breaks differ
    // from the typeset.
    renderer
      .open()
      .then(async () => {
        rendererReady = true;
        // First typeset on the stand-in (source: 'init') — lands the
        // typeset baseline before the user has interacted.
        await runTypeset(STAND_IN, 'init');
      })
      .catch((err) => {
        // Renderer initialisation failed (e.g. Intl.Segmenter unavailable
        // on Firefox <125). Surface plain HTML and the muted notice.
        showFallback(STAND_IN, `BrowserRenderer.open() failed: ${(err as Error).message}`);
      });

    // ─── Editor event listener ────────────────────────────────────────────
    document.addEventListener('pilcrow:editor-changed', (event) => {
      const detail = (event as CustomEvent<EditorChangedDetail>).detail;
      if (!detail || typeof detail.markdown !== 'string') return;
      // If the renderer hasn't finished opening yet, fall back to plain HTML
      // so the user still sees their content. The init resolution above will
      // overwrite with the typeset version once ready.
      if (!rendererReady) {
        host.innerHTML = markdownToPlainHTML(detail.markdown);
        host.dataset.previewState = 'pending';
        return;
      }
      void runTypeset(detail.markdown, detail.source);
    });
  }
</script>

<style>
  /* Label — Inter, small caps via uppercase + tracking, muted. Same recipe
     as Editor.astro's `.editor-label`, rephrased for the preview pane. */
  .preview-label {
    font-family: 'Inter', system-ui, sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }

  /* The frame — the centred container that holds the .post-body host.
     The pane (`section.playground-preview` in `index.astro`) is wide; this
     frame centres the typeset output (which renders at its natural 65ch)
     and provides breathing room around it.

     `min-height: 30rem` reserves vertical space so the JS-disabled SSR
     fallback and the eventual typeset upgrade occupy the same height
     budget — no layout shift on first typeset.

     The pane padding (1.25rem from index.astro) handles the outer inset;
     the inner padding here adds editorial breathing room ABOVE/BELOW the
     typeset output (the 65ch column gives its own horizontal restraint
     via Pilcrow's `.post-body` cascade). */
  .preview-frame {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 30rem;
    padding: 1.5rem 0.5rem;
  }

  /* The .post-body host. Pilcrow's `--prose-measure: 65ch` is set on
     `.post-body` in global.css — by adding the class here, the host
     inherits that custom property AND the body grid + 65ch column
     identically to `pilcrow.page/posts/<slug>/`. The typeset that
     BrowserRenderer drops in carries no inline width; it sits in the
     65ch prose column naturally.

     The host also picks up `font-family: Fraunces`, `line-height: 1.7`,
     and the colour token cascade — so the SSR fallback paragraph reads
     in the same register as the typeset output that will replace it. */
  #playground-preview-host {
    /* Width: let the .post-body grid do its job. The grid is 0 | 65ch |
       2rem | 25ch (~92ch total at the body root). Inside the playground
       pane (which is wider than 65ch on desktop but narrower than ~92ch
       in the 1fr/1fr layout below), we want the prose column to land
       centred. Setting width: 100% + max-content lets the .post-body
       Grid resolve to its natural width but never overflow the pane. */
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 65ch;
  }

  /* Override .post-body's bottom margin on its last paragraph so the
     reserved frame height isn't padded twice. Targets only the preview
     host so .post-body elsewhere on the site is unaffected. */
  #playground-preview-host > p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* Failure notice — Inter, muted, single line. Hidden by default;
     surfaced by the script via `hidden` attribute toggle. */
  .preview-fallback-notice {
    font-family: 'Inter', system-ui, sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    text-align: center;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  /* On narrow viewports, drop the centred-frame inset so the prose has
     room to breathe in the pane. The 65ch max-width on the host already
     provides the column constraint; we just want less side gutter. */
  @media (max-width: 767px) {
    .preview-frame {
      padding: 1rem 0;
    }
  }
</style>
